This place is great! Arturo was so helpful and honest, wonderful customer service throughout the whole experience.  I left my phone number with the girls at the front desk, with description of what I was looking for in a patio set.  You don‚Äôt expect to get such personal and attentive service from a liquidator. But a few weeks later, Arturo called me! Texted pictures of exactly the one I wanted!!! I ran down and purchased it, and paid for the reasonable and quick delivery, next day. He even had tested the fire table and sent me a video showing me how to light it. He also located a missing cushion(in a warehouse! Talk about dedication) and has the delivery guys bring it to me next day. I am happy with my purchase and their excellent customer service.</review>

<user_id>117751432271613121162< /user_id><username>Emily Jean< /username><time>1617080521631< /time>< Rating>

< Review>
Not ADA Accessable! There's handicapped parking and a ramp to enter the building, but the entire interior of the warehouse isn't wheelchair accessible. A lot of the outdoor space is the same. The parking situation isn't ideal. There's only about 10 parking spaces so you usually have to park in the neighborhood. Most items don't have listed pricing and some things are overpriced. Have google handy when you go so you make sure you're getting a fair price. The employees don't wear uniforms or name tags so it can be a bit difficult to find assistance for pricing. With that said, you can definitely find some gems here. We bought 2 kayaks here for $150 a piece. They were brand new and sell for about $650 each. One of them needed a small patch, but other than that, they were in perfect condition.< /Review>

The prices are similar to brand new products at a retail store and the lady that works there, who is always there won't haggle!

Shopping here is like shopping at a retail store without the benefits. You won't get your money back if the product is defective or you don't like it. Instead you are forced to exchange it for the same product or one of of equal value. If you can find something you want.< /text>

Decent bargains, Coffee makers, rice cookers, electronics, suitcases, washers dryers, open box buys. You need to make sure you check to see if things work before you leave. I think items are only returnable for store credit. Some things look like used/returns, but over all I think there are pretty good bargains to be found. They do cater to Spanish speaking but I found that they do speak English and they are very helpful. The walkways are packed to the gills with inventory, stacks and stacks of boxes of items. I will definitely be shopping there again.< /review>

GREAT VALUES ON USED REFRIGERATOR, WASHER, AND DRYER!
Amazing customer service by professional staff. Byron answered all of my questions and then delivered and installed my appliances the same day I bought them.
I bought a used full-size GE refrigerator ($350, 30"W X 30"D X 66"H) that was clean inside and out, a great buy despite two small dents on the right exterior wall.

<Text>Firstly, I ordered delivery from GrubHub. Estimated delivery time was 25 minutes, but it actually didn't arrive until 1 hour, 45 minutes later. When I called to ask them if the order was on it's way a little over an hour after the order was placed, they said it should arrive in 5 minutes max - but it took an additional 40 minutes.

The pizza wasn't hot, but it was decent enough. I would have awarded 3 Stars if not for the following.. Tl;Dr: Never trust a restaurant that doesn't know the difference between cake and pie.

The chocolate cake I ordered was, in fact, pie. As a cake lover who usually passes on pie altogether, I was very disappointed with the discovery.

Please note the menu reads only "Chocolate Cake," with no description. So I called Supremo Pizza to suggest they change their menu to accurately reflect the nature of this dessert... a chocolate cream pie... so others in the future don't make the mistake. I wish I had recorded the conversation, because it was ridiculous.

Me: "Hi! I just ordered delivery, and I wanted to let you know the chocolate cake listed on your menu is actually chocolate cream pie."
Supremo: "How do you know it's not cake?"
Me: "... There's no cake in the dessert. It's chocolate cream pie."
Supremo: "How do you know it's called chocolate cream pie?"
Me: "Because I've had both cake and pie before, and this is pie."

He then proceeded to argue with me that the dessert was cake, simply due to the fact the supplier labels it cake on the box. So I described to him what makes a pie a pie, and what makes a cake a cake, and he still argued with me.

I had to remind him multiple times I wasn't calling for anything but to suggest they just change their menu listing to pie! Or at least add a description of the dessert - a chocolate cookie crust filled with chocolate mousse and topped with cool whip. (i.e. not cake... if we want to get really specific, it more closely resembles the definition of a tart, an open-faced pastry crust with filling.)

Overall, he was just quite rude to me, and all I was suggesting was a change of a word on their menu. At the end he offered to give me more cake for free with my next order. BUT IT'S NOT CAKE. DO NOT WANT. Literally just wanted a "Oops sorry about that, we'll fix our menu to better reflect the item."

But I got no apology, no assurance they'd correct their menu, nothing - but they did blame their supplier for labeling it wrong, which tells me no one there is able to discern the difference between cake and pie without someone telling them so. And also blamed me, for apparently not being happy with the "cake" they sent me.

I've included pictures of the "cake" Supremo sent me, and the images when you search Google for "Chocolate Cream Pie" and "Chocolate Cake." It's very, very obviously, Chocolate Cream Pie.

GOOD DAY SIR.< /Text>< GmapID>

<text>DO NOT ORDER PIZZA FROM HERE!!!!

Let me first start by saying I work in the service industry and have really high standards for service. Eat24 and Ryan the customer service rep that I spoke to was wonderful and exceeded my expectations.

Everything was going wrong with my order. I ordered 10 pizzas for my staff of 30+ people. Their lunches are 45 min. and assigned ahead of time with the first lunches starting at 12pm and going until 2pm. I thought I would have plenty of time to get my pizza by the noon lunches as I ordered at 10:40 am. Even chose a different pizza place than I usually order from as it was one of the few that had delivery that early. It said expected delivery would be 30-45 min but I soon after got a text saying the restaurant confirmed delivery time of 12:10pm. Not ideal but I was ok with that timing.

I went outside at 12:00 to wait curbside for the driver with a cart. At 12:25 was when I first did an online chat with I think her name was Adel from Eat24. She called the restaurant for me and confirmed the driver was on his way. She also gave me a discount because I had to wait. She said the driver was in traffic and the restaurant was busy and they apologized for the delay saying he would be here soon.

Next I contacted Eat24 again at 1:00pm and this time spoke to Ryan and explained the situation. At this point my staff that had been promised lunches had to either not eat or buy their own food. My boss was upset and I had a large department full of employees that were disappointed. For most people in my department paying rent is a struggle and most are working 2-3 jobs, so you can imagine getting free lunch is a really nice thing for them. Ryan called the restaurant for me again and again they said that the restaurant told them the driver was stuck in traffic (there wasn't over an hour of traffic for the usual 10 min drive) and would be her in 10- 15 mins.

The lunch ended up not arriving until 1:30pm and the pizza was barely warm. The driver was apologetic and said traffic was bad because the Tunnel was closed. Afterwards I verified online that the tunnel was indeed open. According to google maps with traffic the longest route would have been 18 mins. I felt lied to and felt like I let down my employees. The one good thing of this entire experience was my interactions with EAT24. They were with me throughout every step of the way and even called me to follow up after the food was delivered. At which point they got my feedback that I didn't feel like the discount I was given earlier was enough to make up for the experience and service I received from the pizza place. Ryan was proactive and called the owner of the pizza place to see what more he could do for me. Honestly I felt like the pizza place should have done more to make up for their terrible service and outright lies but Eat24 did all they could for me and I will continue to be a supporter of Eat24 and tell friends and family to use it as well. Eat 24 is honest, reliable, and supportive service even when everything else seems to be going wrong. It is a wonderful app with great customer service reps.

Thank you for making this terrible day better for me.

Dominique<//text>< Time>

Anyway the end of the month was fast approaching. I had a week to get find a place, see it, get approved, all that bollocks.
In came Nikki to save the day and situation. She took an interest in getting me in despite of all the red tape and communication hassles associated with renting in California. She took the time to show me all the available floor plans in person and to actually take me to the units rather than showing an idealized and inaccurate "model" apartment or even worse, pictures. The best part was the fact she answered all my questions and had the place ready.
The overall vibe of Salishan is as good as it gets for someone new to the community. Always a crew of people making sure the grounds look good, no litter about and actual parking spaces near my unit. My last place I had to practically hail a cab to my car it was so far away- not fun after a days work. It was a real team effort to get me in despite typical paperwork issues (on my part) as I am used to a simpler process back East where I am from.
There were a couple minor issues (sticky bedroom lock and slightly clogged bathroom sink). I let Nikki know and the next day Nick and his associate from maintenance fixed the issues and were great conversation. Also, the buildings numbers are not particularly well displayed, but a map is given to new tenants.
I've rented many places coast to coast and Salishan stands out. Everything works and is in optimal condition in the unit. I look forward to the events and warmer weather where I can use the many amenities like Basketball Courts and Tennis. Meanwhile I can use the indoor fitness center and Racquetball court.
My first few nights I slept very well, which is a good sign for those who travel a lot. It's very quiet and tucked away from the main roads with no trains honking at all hours like the first place I almost moved to.< /review>< Pictures>

All auto shops were closed as it was a Saturday and holiday weekend. Autozone employee recommended giving Affordable Auto Repair a call, saying sometimes they answer on their days off. <Review>This place has a lot to offer. Fresh produce, dairy, canned goods and fresh meats.
There us quite a choosing of products in cookware, eating utensils and other kitchen items.
I love the tea section where you can find strains that most stores don't carry. My favorite ginseng comes in many varieties.
Lots of sweets from all around the world.
Spices, yes they have them.
Also they have a variety of beers from different countries.
Many more items as well as at the checkout there is a bakery with lots of treats. Also in that area is a food court with international meals.

<UserId.>117884723316674414161< /UserId.><username>Tony Smith</username><Time>1601463340363< /Time>< rate>
1</rate>
<text>If you buy the bread from their bakery then
Do not lose your receipt!!
There might be bugs in your bread.

I found bugs in the bread from their bakery. Twice in a row!!!!!
First one was from their soboro bread
And second one was from mommos? Bread.

I know but this is my first fault.
First one was even a live fruit fly. I didn't complain about first one because i was too tired to go back to KP.
But after i found bugs from second one (not even one) i had to.

After that i went to their customer service and customer service lady asked me if i have a receipt. Which i didn't have.
I know it's my fault that i lost the reciept but i don't usually expect bugs from the bread and keep the reciept for that reason.

But if the receipt were really matter, they could've checked their camera. It's everywhere.
Customer service lady said without receipt she won't do anything about my problem. Didn't even check up my bread.
It was really disappointing.
I go to KP at least twice a week. And can't be more disappointed.

Fun place to shop! Feels more like a field trip than a simple trip to a store. They have their covid act together with social distancing, hand sanitizer and plastic gloves available. KP International Market is a great asset to the Sacramento region and I look for excuses to go. The downside is that it's a bit far from my home so not exactly convenient.</review>

< text>
KP International Market / Koreana Plaza is adjoining. This place is like an adventure of discovery! Foods from all over the globe essentially.  Prices are comparable, and many specials throughout. The day I visited, the "Pocky" cookie vendor had a booth setup in the store, and if you bought 3 cookie packages you get a free insulated zippered grocery bag.  There is a food court on the Plaza entrance,  and in the grocery entrance there is also a small booth to buy freshly made Korean street food fare. Happy shopping!<//text>

< Review>
KP is great for just about everything and particularly for hard to asian items. They have my favorite Lao Gan Ma chili sauce, a billion different gochujangs, tons of different ramen, and their produce section is always fresh and stocked with stuff you may not see elsewhere like those long skinny eggplants (the only kind I like). They also have Indian, Mexican, and Eastern European stuff, and a small selection of American groceries. The store is massive and often busy but the staff are super helpful, even when I'm horribly mispronouncing a random item I'm trying to locate amongst the maze of aisles.</Review>

<Name>Kelly C<//Name>< text>
The produce is extravagant.  So much selection. Chinese eggplant, Japanese  eggplant,  Italian eggplant,  Indian eggplant,  Thai eggplant,  baby  eggplant...the only one that I didn't see was the "normal" Globe eggplant. Fresh Thai basil, Italian basil,  mint, coriander  and  tons of  other greens  that I only read about in cookbooks.  Only two types of tomatoes Roma and on-the-vine though.  Ok section of fruit lower prices than Raley's however they  varied in size and color, so only got grapes and bananas. The other sections were ok because the products were  in its own  language and I wearied over  picking  them up to read the U.S. labeling.  It's  definitely for people  who already know about the food.  There's one entrance where there's a table for one to put on protective gloves,  then another table to put on the hand sanitizer and a guard  at the entry point  to ensure compliance with mask, gloves and sanitizer.  I stayed  too long  in there looking at  everything because my hands  were  sweaty and my mask was making it hard to  breathe. The  only way out is through check out. Once  through check out, you are in the food  court  area.  Don't  make  a mistake like me and  try to  enter the market from the check out area  because  the guards will stop you  from  going  in. Also, the bathroom is  outside of the market and  you will have to leave your cart inside  the  market,  make sure you let the guard know that you are just  going  to  the bathroom.   They will give you instructions how to use the temporary lockers. There's no  bread or cereal aisle however there's a  bakery in the food court that sells milk toast and buns.<//text>

< review>
One of my favorite places for a grocery haul, especially for ethnic foods. As a meat and seafood lover, I'd go there to pick up speciality cuts not available at a conventional grocery stores, farmer's markets, butcher's shops, or meat delivery services. Also has a great food court (although I do not usually eat there). Also conveniently located next to the light rail station.</review>

<user_id>114798471821285887995<//user_id><name>Zach Isnec< /name><date>1621549109046</date><rate>5<//rate>< text>
This store has something for everyone. Rice, noodles, meats, Couque D'Asse.  What's Couque D'Asse? It's the thing when you get a fingerling cookie and put something inside of it. Usually a cream filling. Sometimes it's sweet, sometimes it's salty. Normally it depends on what the package handler has eaten recently.
Srsly though, this place is great. About half of it is an Asian supermarket that can fly with the best of them. The remaining other half-ish is comprised of worldly foods. The former Soviet Bloc food section and selections  are surprisingly nice.  Not like a surprise Couque D'Asse. One is never prepared for a surprise Couque D'Asse.
7/7, would recommend to anybody!</text>

<username>Liquifire< /username><pics>None<//pics>< date>

<userid>103144120972499820305</userid>< review>
The staff leave much to be desired in the way of common courtesy and equality. I've come here frequently, as much of my cooking requires what are considered hard to find ingredients in Sacramento. One thing I noticed is that there seems to be a subtle undercurrent of racism amongst certain employees. My best guess is that the gap is due to a difference in linguistic familiarity....if you speak the same dialect, you'll probably get a friendly reception aiming to build rapport. On the other hand, failure to do so seems to elicit coldness and a dismissive attitude. I love the multicultural groceries they offer, but this feeling I get is really awkward. It's like I'm an unwanted pet or guest. I consider myself a gentleman, and always do my best to conduct my behavior as such, but these trivialities don't have any bearing on how I'm treated. Additionally, the food court has markedly declined. One of their best restraunts closed, and the other 3 don't offer anything worth what they charge. For these reasons, and much mote, 2 stars is being generous.< /review>

I want to preface my review by saying that I love the actual grocery store/market. However, the KP International food court is a joke. The food is all bland and tastes like they reheat it all in the back.

The MOST AGGRIVATING ASPECT of the food court is the HORRIBLE costumer service. I mean I've eaten here less then 5 times and have heard agruments with the costumers with the staff half the time. I never believed it would happen to me until today where the Korean place gave us the wrong order but absolutely would not take it back to give us what we actually ordered because we had already taken it from the counter. We literally didn't touch the food  and took it back 30 seconds after we got it from the counter! I wouldn't really care about this because mistakes happen but the way the cashier rudely talked down to me as if I did something wrong is absolutely not the way to treat a costumer.

If you're hungry and considering the KP International food court, do yourself a favor and go to any of the better restaurants down the street. The food will taste way more and flavorful and authentic. The price will  be similar but other restaurants will have wayyy better costumer service.<//review>

Crazy amazing selection in foreign foods. From Asian, Middle Eastern, European, Hispanic and more. Fruit and veg section is awesome in selection. Regular good deals on meat prices and you can ask the butchers for specific cuts at times (had them cut me 2+ in. Porterhouses on more than one occasion). <user>113029829249756660129< /user><name>Pamela W.< /name><Date>1533138996771<//Date><Rate>3< /Rate><Text>This was my first time to the international market and I was really excited to see so many new and different foods and grocery items available for such reasonable prices... Also I'm excited about the seafood and butcher selections... Bought two nice big halibut steaks for only $20 last week which would normally be closer to 50 and it was absolutely amazing... highly recommend

July 2018 update.... the seafood several times since my last review however I have to disclose that the last two times I had halibut in the salmon it had numerous worms in it... The hell of it had red worms the same and has white worms it really freaked me out... The last time I saw worms in Market Fish was about 12 years ago when I had red snapper to Safeway... I realize bottom feeders will tend to have worms but I believe that a proper fishmonger or store will do candling and remove most of the worms when possible these worms are on the surface and obviously had not been candled or physically checked.... I took out the worms as best I could from the halibut and cooked it extra long two temperature that would kill them however I only ate a little bit and me and my son both had stomach aches later although I never told him about the worms my stomach hasn't seemed right for about a week after eating it so I don't think I'll eat the fish there again... I did call them and brought it to their attention in the fish department said they had never seen worms ever ever on their fish which to me sounds not accurate cuz we all know fish has worms in it from time to time I left a message for the manager to call me back and he never called me back... I contacted health department and they indicated that worms will have fish on them and it's not a health violation but rather a customer service issue... I found that strange as I saw many news articles about Costco fish having worms in the health department shutting them down so not really clear about this but I'm not comfortable buying Seafood there any longer... Although I did read you can soak it in cold water and when I did that with the salmon the worms did come out but again I think I prefer to buy wild-caught frozen fish from now on so I don't have to deal with worms.... if anyone has any other feedback I love to hear it because I was so excited about the great tasting seafood at great prices< /Text>< Pictures>

< review>
Great place to shop for imported food.  Mostly Oriental, but a good assortment of eastern Euopean as well.  The produce isle includes locally grown yet unusual fruits and vegetables.

The food court has two food bars.  One with sushi & Korean selections and the other has "Americanized" oriental & Mexican.  Plus a Korean restaurant.

Other related shopping includes oriental kitchen pots & gadgets.< /review>

<Rate>5< /Rate><text>Honestly the best international store around for many miles. They have some of the best prices for fruits and veggies. Not always quality but when your cooking with it, it doesn't need to look perfect.

The clearance bin is a hit or miss depending on day but always interesting to look through. They have a pretty good selection of products for a wide variety of nations. Japanese, Korean, Indian, philipino, Russian, European etc....

They have a rewards system that you can sign up for. A dollar earns you a point that is worth about a penny towards their food court.

Speaking of which, they also have a nice variety when it comes to their food court. Burgers, hotdogs, Vietnamese pho and Bahn mi, Mexican food, Japanese sushi and bentos, Korean dishes, etc..... There are lots of tables to eat as well as a large screen with a projector that plays some funny prank show.

During the holiday season they have free picture taking with an Easter Bunny or santa. Not sure about other holidays.  Very well done for a free photo. Lastly the staff is always friendly and tries to be helpful. I say try because they don't always communicate well. Overall, one of my favorite places to shop.</text>< pictures>

<user_id>116352581032780554430</user_id>< Review>
There is the most comprehensive selection for any home cook to be found. My only reason for four out of five stars is price. Across the board there are few areas they are competitive in pricing. Retail costs similar to Raley's and sometimes as high as Whole Foods. Produce and fish quality are well worth that price however packaged goods with high preservatives levels and long shelf life are priced much higher than market. However the selection all Under One Roof does mollify the most visceral argument for the high cost.</Review>

<review>Great prices on meat all the time. Also had a great assortment of speciality Asian food products<//review><Rate>5</Rate></record></dataset><record>
<user_id>101319605968639283215< /user_id><user_name>Melissa Ratner<//user_name><time>1541122322831< /time><Rate>4</Rate>< review>
Overall, I love this place. Excellent produce selection as well as a wide variety of ethnic products that aren't commonly stocked at other stores. Can't beat the price on the produce and many of the everyday items are reasonably priced as well. Meat and deli department also have a terrific selection and extremely competitive pricing. The only reason I'm not giving this place five stars is because some of their items are horribly overpriced. Items like salad dressing, detergent, etc. are almost twice what you would pay in other stores. However, they are also very conveniently located next to Target, Walmart, and many other stores so it's easy to pop into another place for the items that are overpriced at KP.<//review>

<rate>2<//rate><review>The market gets 5 stars, the hot food section gets -3...

The market has an incredible selection of foods you would have difficulties find anywhere else. Their selection of slavic foods is good. Their mainland asian and pacific island selection even better. The produce is mostly fresh and prices are reasonable. Their frozen choices are great.

The hot food section has interesting choices, most of which are priced a little too high. Not much, just enough to be annoying. Here is where the service is lacking. You cannot simply get a small cup of water to go with your meal. When I asked, I was directed to a vending machine to buy a bottle of water.

What the...

The price wasn't bad, but the bottle was room temperature. Look, a family who has small children doesn't necessarily want to buy soda for them. The cost of the food should cover a small cup of water.

Not having water is not good customer service.

I am going to use the market. I'll be dammed if I ever use the food court again...< /review><userid>114331626537444941470</userid><Pics>None</Pics></record></dataset><record>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
Always have enjoyed shopping here. KP market carries a very wide of choices -- Japanese and Korean noodles, spices and sauces. All sorts of Frozen and fresh sea food.

The bakery section has regular bread, Mexican tortia, middle eastern pita bread and everything conceivable.

The spices section same, spices from around the world.

Our favorite, beet juice from Georgia and Slavania, pickled and fermented foods from all over Europe.

The produce section has vegetables for Asian -- Chinese brocallie, Okinawan potatoes,... Korean reddish,... Including all regular items such as tomato, bell peppers, lemon,..

Just a delight to see wonderful selection from all over the world.<//text>

<text>Kp is a great store for finding all those weird ingredients you need. It has pretty much everything! I have been shopping here for a long time and have never had any issues, except for today, and I won't be shopping here any longer.

I bought a boba smoothie from the food court and then proceeded to the other side of the store to get a cart and do my shopping. When I went outside to get a cart I was told I cannot bring food in the store.

The sign on the door says no OUTSIDE food or drink, and I had bought the smoothie literally a couple minutes prior inside the store. I pointed this out to the security guy and he said "too bad, it doesn't matter." I pointed out to him again that the sign says outside food and drink and he again said too bad and pointed to the sign that says "we reserve the right to refuse service to anyone"

Honestly it wouldn't have even bothered me that much if he had cared to be even somewhat polite. I asked a cashier inside if I could speak to a manager and she acted like I had just asked the hardest thing in the world. I told her what I wanted to talk to the manager about and she told me to go talk to security.

Thanks a lot lol. This store has never had good customer service and it has never bothered me, but these two employees are the reason I won't be returning.

<user_name>Kurumi Aoyama-Baker („Åè„Çã/Kuru)< /user_name><time>1555206153030< /time><Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Love the place!
It's so much fun to just be in the store. There are so many things you can get from this store. The main products you can get are, of course Korean foods. We always get a big bin of Kimchee. Their price for Kimchee cannot be beat.
We also get prepared Korean foods like seaweed salad, radish Kimchee, etc.
They have Japanese foods as well. We get Japanese seasonings such as Dashi (Bonito soup base, ) hot pot soup base, and hurikake (rice seasoning flakes.)
They have sample stations and their sample foods are always so delicious that it is guaranteed to make me want to purchase the foods. The sample ladies are always nice and friendly.
I wish this place was closer to where I live.< /review>

<Text>I love KPI! This place is a cook's dream! If you're looking for a huge variety of inexpensive produce this is the place.They also have 1.5 aisles of greens (pea shoots, asian chives++), fresh peas & garbanzos, banana flowers, bok choy (& its ten cousins). Add to that a wall+ of spices & herbs (a couple fresh, the rest dried). Frozen fish & seafood, 6 kinds of tofu, frozen shao mae, fresh & frozen noodles. They just started carrying high quality frozen Indian foods & breads (including 25 packs of frozen paratha. There's tons of frozen foods, like gyoza (chicken, pork, veggies, & combos), AND lumpia...

Let's make this easier: This place is FULL of all kinds of:
‚Ä¢ Asian food supplies (like an aisle of soy sauce. Plus prefab tamarind sauce & other Asian sauces;
‚Ä¢ Some basic American staples (milk, juices, cheeses, deli meats);
‚Ä¢ Some Eastern European (desserts, sausages, pastas & cheeses);
‚Ä¢ Hispanic food supplies (canned & dry ingredients and a Tortilleria);
‚Ä¢ Fresh meats (all kinds) & seafood.

‚óè EXCEPT for fresh East Indian paneer ‚óè
I haven't found that...ONE...thing. Seriously.

There's also cookware & kitchen tools; sake sets; ramen bowls; an aisle of sauces & soups; tea; alcohol (beer & wine); soda, basic & household items (paper towels++).

OOPS I forgot that there's ALSO an Eastern European bakery; 3-4 cafeteria style restaurants; a jewelry store and a Bubble tea place. I hear they've got the best pho you can find. There's a lot of indoor seating for you to eat at & a gorgeous, waterfall-type fountain you can sit at & listen to it's hypnotic sound.

There's also the most aware, helpful & friendly Security team to keep an eye on you in the parking lot (ladies check out the Security guards cause some of them are HOT). The lot has video cameras too & beautiful lights in all the trees at the holidays. KP Billiards is next door with Manny at the cocktail bar.

Set aside 1-2 hours just to figure out that's in this MASSIVE store. It's open until 10:00PM on some nights.< /Text><pictures>None< /pictures><Rating>5</Rating><Name>Sue Goodrich<//Name><Response>None< /Response>< UserId.>

I say Asian because it has more than just Korean specialties, but Japanese, Indian, and Hawaiian to name a few. The produce includes ingrediants you won't find at your local market, and the meat and fish from the butcher include cuts you won't find even at Seafood City.

<Time>1494771255985</Time><rating>4<//rating>< text>
KP Plaza is a wonderful place to find international food staples and specialty grocery items. Inside you will find fresh seafood, specialty cuts of meat, freshly made kimbap and they also have a section making fresh tortillas to take home.

The food court has Mexican, Chinese, Korean food and even has a pastry booth where you can buy a variety of sweets or savory pies to go.  If you would rather eat a little more upscale, you can chose to dine at the Red Alcove an excellant Korean BBQ place or sing karaoke at KP Karaoke both connected to the plaza.

Parking is easy and the Gold line light rail station is right outside making it a convenient stop.<//text>

<user>102208815034885552238</user><username>Sue Goodrich<//username><time>1552171580236<//time>< review>
I love KPI! This place is a cook's dream! If you're looking for a huge variety of inexpensive produce this is the place.They also have 1.5 aisles of greens (pea shoots, asian chives++), fresh peas & garbanzos, banana flowers, bok choy (& its ten cousins). Add to that a wall+ of spices & herbs (a couple fresh, the rest dried). Frozen fish & seafood, 6 kinds of tofu, frozen shao mae, fresh & frozen noodles. They just started carrying high quality frozen Indian foods & breads (including 25 packs of frozen paratha. There's tons of frozen foods, like gyoza (chicken, pork, veggies, & combos), AND lumpia...

Let's make this easier: This place is FULL of all kinds of:
‚Ä¢ Asian food supplies (like an aisle of soy sauce. Plus prefab tamarind sauce & other Asian sauces;
‚Ä¢ Some basic American staples (milk, juices, cheeses, deli meats);
‚Ä¢ Some Eastern European (desserts, sausages, pastas & cheeses);
‚Ä¢ Hispanic food supplies (canned & dry ingredients and a Tortilleria);
‚Ä¢ Fresh meats (all kinds) & seafood.

‚óè EXCEPT for fresh East Indian paneer ‚óè
I haven't found that...ONE...thing. Seriously.

There's also cookware & kitchen tools; sake sets; ramen bowls; an aisle of sauces & soups; tea; alcohol (beer & wine); soda, basic & household items (paper towels++).

OOPS I forgot that there's ALSO an Eastern European bakery; 3-4 cafeteria style restaurants; a jewelry store and a Bubble tea place. I hear they've got the best pho you can find. There's a lot of indoor seating for you to eat at & a gorgeous, waterfall-type fountain you can sit at & listen to it's hypnotic sound.

There's also the most aware, helpful & friendly Security team to keep an eye on you in the parking lot (ladies check out the Security guards cause some of them are HOT). The lot has video cameras too & beautiful lights in all the trees at the holidays. KP Billiards is next door with Manny at the cocktail bar.

Set aside 1-2 hours just to figure out that's in this MASSIVE store. It's open until 10:00PM on some nights.<//review>

<Pics>None< /Pics><Review>I'll start off by saying, this place is "HUGE!" This place has everything that you need to preparing an Asian meal.

I made the mistake of parking, which I thought was the end of the store!  Wrong...  This store runs almost a block long!

This store is like a grocery store, fish market, bakery, etc.  They carry a lot of stuff in bulk which saves money had you made the same purchase in another store.

Their foodcourt has a variety of different meals but leans more towards the Asian cuisine.

I particularly gravitated towards their Korean B-B-Q where every table has a grill right at your table to cook your order.

Overall this is definitely a good place to shop or to grab a bite.< /Review>< Name>

<Review>They run this place like a mom and pop back in Korea. I bought Cham Kimchi  because they were out of my usual Manna brand and it turned out to be 2 weeks old. They told me over the phone to bring it back, and then  when I got there they said that they couldn't refund citing the store policy.  Selling 2 week old Kimchi is a fraud to begin with, and they lied  claiming they never sell 2 weeks old kimchi. What a fraud. I left $18 jar on the counter and left. They wasted not only my $18, but also an hour on 20 mile drive.

I've never had this kind of problem in the South Bay where they have several Korean stores. In Sacramento, this is the only major store and they run it as such.  I can't wait for H-Mart to come  in and give them some competition. Till then, stay away from this place and Cham Kimchi. I'll try Smile Market the next time.</Review>< pictures>

< Rating>

<review>Probably the best all around grocery store in Rancho Cordova. Very good deals on fish, meat, vegetables, and ethnic foods like Indian, Chinese, Korean (of course, in the name!), Russian, and Mexican. Lots of stuff here that you can't typically find at traditional stores, like bittermelons, opo squash, sing qua squash, bok choy. Being Korean in origin, the selection in Korean food is unparalleled for the Sacramento region. The selection of other ethnic foods, especially Asian food, is also impressive. The food court is similarly very large and quite good. For major sporting events and occasions - like the Olympics, World Cup, and Superbowl - this is a nice place to hang out and eat some pretty good food that is fast casual and multiethnic.</review>< pictures>

< Time>
1601450998702</Time>
<UserId.>110762261247234042631<//UserId.><gmap_id>0x809add6cec217ce7:0xd2c4a926a3f8f3ff< /gmap_id><response>None< /response>< review>
Not the best Korean market I've been to, but better than nothing. Disappointing produce, almost all shrinkwrapped, limited variety, if you are looking for Korean veg. Many of the people working here know nothing about Korean food. In the fish department, no one knew how to filet a fish! (I do, but I was feeling lazy.) they have removed the live tanks and the fish selection is small unless you are looking for salmon. OTOH, you can get Filipino, Russian, Mexican and more here. Decent selection of Korean basics, including Kimchi from Korea and a local non-MSG variety, but also cheap Kimchi from China.  Overall, I  found this market grimy and unpleasant to shop in. The international variety is interesting, but if you are looking for Korean supplies, you'll do better at Smile. The meat and prepared Banchan are overpriced. I'm always sorry when I decide to shop here, they don't even carry my favorite soju. If you'rr looking for a lot of different stuff you might like it here, but it's not for me. Watch out for the pastry shop. The things I bought were stale, with soggy pastry and dried out fillings.< /review>
